  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        A partition of <m>[a,b]</m> is a finite set
        <me>
          P=\set{x_0,x_1,x_2,\cdots,x_n}
        </me>
        such that <m>a=x_{0}</m>, <m>b=x_{n}</m>, and <m>x_{0}&#x3C;x_{1}&#x3C;x_{2}&#x3C;\cdots&#x3C;x_{n}</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Given a partition <m>\set{\seq x0n}</m> of <m>[a,b]</m>, for each subinterval <m>[x_{i-1},x_{i}]</m>, we denote:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>m_i \amp = \inf\set{f(x):x\in[x_{i-1},x_i]}</mrow>
        <mrow>M_i \amp = \sup\set{f(x):x\in[x_{i-1},x_i]}</mrow>
      </md>

      <p>
        Now we can define the upper sum as
        <me>
          U(f,P)=\sum_{i=1}^{n} M_{i}\cdot(x_{i}-x_{i-1})
        </me>
        and the lower sum as
        <me>
          L(f,P)=\sum_{i=1}^{n} m_{i}\cdot(x_{i}-x_{i-1})\text{.}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        A partition <m>Q</m> of <m>[a,b]</m> is a refinement of <m>P</m> if <m>P\subseteq Q</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        If so, then
        <me>
          U(f,P)\ge U(f,Q)\quad\text{and}\quad L(f,P)\le L(f,Q)\text{.}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        If <m>P</m> is a partition of <m>[a,b]</m>, then <m>L(f,P)\le U(f,P)</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        If <m>P_{1}</m> and <m>P_{2}</m> are any partitions of <m>[a,b]</m>, then
        <me>
          L(f,P_{1})\le U(f,P_{2})\text{.}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Let <m>f:[a,b]\to\bb R</m> be a bounded function and let <m>\cl P</m> be the collection of <em>all</em> partition of <m>[a,b]</m>.
        The upper integral of <m>f</m> is defined to be
        <me>
          U(f)=\inf_{P\in\cl P}U(f,P)
        </me>
        and the lower integral is
        <me>
          L(f)=\sup_{P\in\cl P}L(f,P)
        </me>
        If <m>L(f)=U(f)</m>, we say that <m>f</m> is Darboux integrable.
        This is equivalent to being Riemann integrable.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        If <m>m=\inf\limits_{a\le x\le b}f(x)</m> and <m>M=\sup\limits_{a\le x\le b}f(x)</m>, then
        <me>
          m(b-a)\le L(f)\le U(f)\le M(b-a)\text{.}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
